      "ESSeqNum": 1,
      "FacilityID": 1000089124,
      "SummaryText": "accidents have occurred in the last five years involving a regulated substance that could affect any external public or environmental receptors.\n5.\tEmergency Response Program\n\nThe Facility has a well-trained Emergency Response Team capable of responding to emergencies. The Community is informed about ongoing emergencies via the LEPC, Sheriff's department and/or Southeast Texas Alert Network.\n\n6.\tPlanned changes to improve safety\nThe facility plans to:\n-\tContinuously perform evaluation of Anomalies, Near Misses, and Incidents; \n-\tPerform Audits and regulatory inspections as required;\n-\tEquip some tanks with overfill protection as the Site deems necessary;\n-\tUpdate procedures and conduct training on a scheduled basis and as necessary;\n-\tConduct some Infrastructure Upgrades to the electrical system and obtain a new Motor control center (MCC) when able; and\n-\tModernize the loading rack to ensure the availability of safety shower on the loading platform."
    },
    {
      "ESSeqNum": 0,
      "FacilityID": 1000089124,
      "SummaryText": "1.\tAccidental Release Prevention and Emergency Response.\nThe Total Cray Valley - Beaumont Plant has an RMP Policy to assure adherence to applicable Federal, State and Local rules and regulations. The Plant could affect outside receptors and complies with the OSHA Process Safety Management (PSM) Standard 29CFR 1910.119 and thus falls under Program 3 of the RMP compliance requirements.\nThe Facility's Integrated Contingency Plan (ICP) or Emergency Response program has been developed and outline in standards, procedures, policies and training. The ICP include procedures for notification of local authorities, regulatory agencies and any potentially affected neighbors.\n2.\tThe Stationary Source and Regulated Substance Handled.\nThe Total Cray Valley - Beaumont Plant produces C5 hydrocarbon resins. These resins have many diverse uses. The covered processes use RMP regulated substances above the planning threshold. These substances are Boron Trifluoride, 1,3-Pentadiene, n-Pentane.\n3.\tChemical Accident Prevention.\nThis Facility complies with the PSM Standard. Process Hazard Analyses (PHAs) have been conducted on the processes at this Facility. PHAs are also conducted on changes that trigger Management of Change (MOC) process. The original RMP PHAs are revalidated on minimum of a five-year cycle. PSM audits are conducted on a minimum cycle of every three years. The Facility and its equipment are designed in accordance with recognized good engineering practices and standards, such as, ANSI, API, NFPA, ASTM and others as applicable. The Plant has extensive redundant systems to ensure safe operations. Operators are trained and qualified to operate the plant.\nManagement has placed safety and protecting the environment as the highest priorities for operating the Plant. There is a Safety and Security Specialist onsite and extensive interaction with the Corporate HSSE staff to ensure the plant is operated in a safe and environmentally sound manner.\n4.\tFive Years Accident History.\nNo"
    }
  ]
